Only the following locations: Little Lake Field, Big Burn Field, Little Lake, and the overmature stand nearby.	Rare, should probably require documentation as the species isn't normally found anywhere in the county except Big Burn Field.  Historically I had no trouble finding two singing males here, but all was quiet today.  I was biking down the central trail, half asleep and not nearly as observant as I should have been, when I saw a sparrow running full speed down the trail away from me with its wings half open.  Knowing that this in itself was a hilarious anomaly, I assumed that the bird itself must be anomalous-- and it was.  Seen poorly, but well enough.  Also heard chip calls.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS533941073	2021-03-19 09:49:50.883448	31855	species	Grasshopper Sparrow	Ammodramus savannarum			1					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Marquette	US-MI-103		12			Marquette Compost Yard (restricted access)	L4954830	H	46.5667681	-87.3937941	2017-09-18	16:29:00	obsr301832	S39260403	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	140	4.120		1	1		0	1	1			Seen four times over the course of about 15 minutes on and around a weedy hill near the southwest corner of the compost yard. First seen flying away from me, when it flushed from the ground and flew low for a few yards before suddenly plunging headfirst back into vegetation. I noted a short tail, weak fluttery flight, and overall brownish coloration. Based on these observations I immediately suspected Grasshopper. ----The subsequent three sightings were all somewhat prolonged (&gt;15 seconds) and lightly obstructed at very close range as it perched low in tansy stands after being flushed from underfoot. Noted each time were a large flat head, thin but noticeable pale eye ring, rich buffy lores, dark crown with pale median stripe, and dark "j" around the top and back of the auriculars. Underparts were clearly visible twice, and were an unmarked tan except for some limited, diffuse brownish-red streaking at the sides of the breast. The best look I got at it was from no more than six feet away through binoculars, and I was able to note in outstanding detail all of the marks mentioned above in addition to a buffy wash to the auriculars, rich brown scapulars broadly edged with gray, and grayish-brown nape heavily flecked with small brown markings. ----After the fourth sighting I briefly turned my attention to a flock of Clay-colored Sparrows and could not refind it afterward.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS163215457	2021-03-24 16:18:46.885815	31855	species	Grasshopper Sparrow	Ammodramus savannarum			1					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Saginaw	US-MI-145	US-MI_1644	12	USFWS_750		Shiawassee NWR--Woodland Trail	L270887	H	43.3844108	-84.0005570	2012-09-09	07:44:00	obsr147420	S11547741	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	193	4.023		1	1		0	1	1			Juvenile age. At first sighting, the bird was in flight, and appeared as a small, overall light tan, short-tailed sparrow. Then the bird was observed twice while perched low in field vegetation. The first was a back view, and very brief in duration, but darker feathers were apparent, in a scaly pattern. The second perched view was quite prolonged, and was of the front of the body to the feet, and the head from all sides. The small size and relatively large head were readily apparent. The belly and breast were near white, but suffused with a blush of light tan. The upper breast and flanks were marked with fine, short, somewhat diffuse streaks. The throat was light, and unmarked. Overall, the head was light tan, with the relatively large, dark eye, (surrounded by a very narrow but complete light eye ring), appearing quite dominant. The crown had a light tan median stripe, bordered by dark lateral stripes. A narrow dark postocular stripe was present, broadening as it reached the upper rear of the ear covert. (The proceeding color references for the head plumage describe the general appearance, but on the bird itself, the colors were speckled, not solid.)  The beak and feet were flesh color, and the former was relatively long, (for general comparison sake ONLY - like a RWBL beak versus a HOFI beak.) One more view of the bird in flight was obtained, and again the light coloration, overall small size and short tail were noted.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS493431200	2017-05-07 23:26:05	31855	species	Grasshopper Sparrow	Ammodramus savannarum			8					United States	US	Michigan	US-MI	Wayne	US-MI-163		23			Willow Run Airport (restricted access)	L426624	H	42.2326880	-83.5077989	2007-06-06		obsr130801	S36483503	Historical	P62	EBIRD				2	0		0	1	1		birding with Allen Chartier. Reconstructed from old post to Mich-listers: "Yesterday morning (June 6), Neil Gilbert and I set out for birding sites in western Washtenaw County. First, we stopped at Willow Run Airport (Wayne Co.) where we found three singing HENSLOW'S SPARROWS. The birds were at the east end of the airport. On the map in A Birder's Guide to Michigan (page 84), this is south of Tyler Road, on the east side of the north-south road around the airport. There were also Bobolinks in this field, and at least 8 Grasshopper Sparrows at various other places around the airport. A single Western Meadowlark was singing a great distance away, in the middle of the runways, as is often the case here. (Western Meadowlarks arrived here on April 19.)"
